      <subsection>
        <title>Overview</title>
        <p>For our first Preclass Guided Practice, we'll start by reviewing the main resources you have available for reference while learning course material. Other resources for specific lessons will be linked in the relevant Preclass Guided Practice.</p>
        <p>We'll also practice calculating final grades based on several different situations to gain comfort and familiarity with the grading scheme being used in this course. Grades are calculated in a two-stage process, and we will practice both stages.</p>
        <p>Finally, we'll review the <em>division algorithm</em>. While this may seem incredibly basic, it is going to lay the groundwork for much of both classical and modern cryptography. We will be able to trace much of what we learn this semester back to the division algorithm, so we'll take a bit of time to go over it carefully.</p>
        <p>Even though we'll be working almost exclusively with integers this semester, and not other groups, rings, or fields, we'll also look briefly at how this concept generalizes to polynomials, although this work will be done in class.</p>
        <p>Remember, Guided Practice is designed to get you familiar with the language, definitions, and basic computational skills needed to succeed in the classroom activities each class. While there will be a few minutes at the start of class for questions each day for the Guided Practice, you can get immediate help by asking questions on the <c>#guided_practice</c> channel within our course Slack group. It is expected that you have gone through these exercises and that you are prepared to start working with these concepts without any additional lecture or presentation of these ideas once you get to the classroom.</p>
      </subsection>

